59
00:02:39,623 --> 00:02:41,964
the world that would cause any of us to have any stress.

60
00:02:42,986 --> 00:02:46,747
But on top of that, our industry is its own source of stress.

61
00:02:48,107 --> 00:02:49,748
It's a creative work environment.

62
00:02:50,108 --> 00:02:53,069
And what that means is that people are always

63
00:02:53,149 --> 00:02:54,909
critiquing your work, and you're always

64
00:02:55,009 --> 00:02:58,250
putting yourself and your skills and your talent

65
00:02:58,310 --> 00:03:00,731
and what you believe out there for other people to critique.

66
00:03:01,251 --> 00:03:02,971
And that inherently creates stress.

67
00:03:04,912 --> 00:03:07,173
Where it's also an industry of constant change.

68
00:03:07,733 --> 00:03:09,993
So whether it's moving on to a new game,

69
00:03:10,033 --> 00:03:12,234
whether it's new people on the team, people leaving the team,

70
00:03:13,247 --> 00:03:15,448
We're always, even when we make sequels,

71
00:03:15,468 --> 00:03:18,831
we're always having to create new features

72
00:03:19,391 --> 00:03:22,673
and new elements that have never been seen before in games.

73
00:03:22,773 --> 00:03:25,355
It's just the constant flood of change can be overwhelming.

74
00:03:26,976 --> 00:03:28,758
There's also a lot of loss and grief

75
00:03:29,058 --> 00:03:30,279
we don't really discuss.

76
00:03:31,980 --> 00:03:34,442
Even shipping a game that you're proud of

77
00:03:34,622 --> 00:03:37,464
has a certain amount of loss and grief associated with it

78
00:03:37,944 --> 00:03:39,625
because you spent a lot of time with that game.

79
00:03:40,275 --> 00:03:46,000
and having it suddenly out of your life can be something that's hard to deal with. But even more

80
00:03:46,020 --> 00:03:52,144
so, having games canceled and companies close and people leave the team or the industry altogether,

81
00:03:52,164 --> 00:03:59,790
it's definitely cycles of loss and grief mixed in between the joy and creation.

82
00:04:02,132 --> 00:04:06,555
And then most important, I think, in terms of adding stress, we have a silence

83
00:04:06,895 --> 00:04:09,718
endurance culture. And what I mean by that is,

84
00:04:10,455 --> 00:04:18,658
you're expected to endure. You're expected to find ways to cope by yourself. And you're expected

85
00:04:18,718 --> 00:04:22,519
not to complain about it and not to try to make changes. And in fact, trying to make changes is

86
00:04:22,599 --> 00:04:28,220
often seen as complaining. It's seen as a lack of passion. It's seen as you just not being strong

87
00:04:28,280 --> 00:04:34,442
enough for this industry. And that is unfortunate because what that means is we don't fix the

88
00:04:34,482 --> 00:04:38,503
problems that are causing people to feel so much stress. So

89
00:04:39,528 --> 00:04:43,750
The stress that creates burnout and burnout itself often go unrecognized.

90
00:04:44,590 --> 00:04:47,751
So here's some of the ways that you can recognize it in yourself and in others.

91
00:04:47,791 --> 00:04:51,313
There's what everybody looks for, which is that intense anger.

92
00:04:51,333 --> 00:04:52,993
I can't take this anymore.

93
00:04:53,753 --> 00:04:56,975
But there are also other signs like the thousand mile pain stare

94
00:04:56,995 --> 00:05:00,316
that you see from someone who's been crunching for six months now.

95
00:05:02,017 --> 00:05:04,918
There's a frustration and an inability to focus,

96
00:05:04,978 --> 00:05:07,719
and the two really are a self-feeding cycle.

97
00:05:08,550 --> 00:05:10,050
between those two factors.

98
00:05:11,791 --> 00:05:13,852
And there are feelings of worthless and incompetence.

99
00:05:13,892 --> 00:05:16,554
And I want to make sure to separate this out

100
00:05:16,634 --> 00:05:17,714
from imposter syndrome.

101
00:05:18,235 --> 00:05:20,336
Imposter syndrome is when you feel

102
00:05:20,376 --> 00:05:23,497
like you're not good at something you're actually

103
00:05:23,557 --> 00:05:28,020
good at, a specific task or activity or thing

104
00:05:28,140 --> 00:05:29,060
that you're actually good at.

105
00:05:29,961 --> 00:05:32,582
This is feeling worthless and incompetent at everything.

106
00:05:32,962 --> 00:05:36,744
You feel like you just are not worth anything as a person,

107
00:05:37,224 --> 00:05:38,205
not just about the task.

108
00:05:40,568 --> 00:05:44,250
It causes us to disconnect from friends and family and things that we enjoy.

109
00:05:44,851 --> 00:05:49,714
And it also causes physical illness, heart illness, heart disease.

110
00:05:51,035 --> 00:05:55,798
And stress itself can just cause a variety of effects,

111
00:05:56,398 --> 00:05:59,160
including autoimmune disorders on your body.

112
00:05:59,380 --> 00:06:03,163
And that's not to mention, of course, heartburn and ulcer.

113
00:06:03,877 --> 00:06:06,419
So there are a ton of ways to recognize

114
00:06:06,459 --> 00:06:07,420
when burnout is happening,

115
00:06:07,981 --> 00:06:09,682
but usually we discover it way too late.

116
00:06:09,723 --> 00:06:13,206
We figure it out at the point where you

117
00:06:13,446 --> 00:06:15,989
or the person involved just wants to leave the team

118
00:06:16,069 --> 00:06:16,910
or leave the company,

119
00:06:17,030 --> 00:06:19,252
or maybe even leave the whole industry.

120
00:06:20,453 --> 00:06:22,295
And this comes at a really high cost.

121
00:06:24,898 --> 00:06:25,999
In a Deloitte survey, 91%...

122
