00:13:15,784 --> 00:13:19,848
In both cases involving luck, performance increased.

254
00:13:21,890 --> 00:13:25,472
And in fact, we as human beings and all animals, really,

255
00:13:25,612 --> 00:13:27,513
are wired for superstition.

256
00:13:28,814 --> 00:13:31,495
The probably most famous behavioral researcher,

257
00:13:32,196 --> 00:13:35,117
B.F. Skinner, started researching pigeons.

258
00:13:36,058 --> 00:13:40,620
And he set up something to feed the birds at regular intervals.

259
00:13:41,680 --> 00:13:43,882
And what happened was the birds didn't

260
00:13:43,902 --> 00:13:46,123
develop a sense of time and all cluster

261
00:13:46,183 --> 00:13:47,864
around the feeding mechanism at a certain time.

262
00:13:49,383 --> 00:13:51,004
they started acting in a particular way

263
00:13:51,044 --> 00:13:52,965
and started believing that the way they were acting

264
00:13:53,045 --> 00:13:55,486
influenced the arrival of food.

265
00:13:56,187 --> 00:13:58,508
So by the end of the study, 3 quarters of the pigeons

266
00:13:58,608 --> 00:13:59,749
became superstitious.

267
00:14:00,649 --> 00:14:03,011
And for example, one pigeon believed

268
00:14:03,051 --> 00:14:06,353
that turning around in a circle two or three times

269
00:14:06,433 --> 00:14:07,273
was what brought the food.

270
00:14:07,894 --> 00:14:09,875
And most interestingly, it wasn't

271
00:14:10,015 --> 00:14:11,036
turning in any direction.

272
00:14:11,456 --> 00:14:13,677
It was always counterclockwise, that he

273
00:14:13,697 --> 00:14:16,199
would turn counterclockwise two or three times,

274
00:14:16,299 --> 00:14:17,039
and then the food would come.

275
00:14:17,905 --> 00:14:23,730
So if birds can become superstitious without any prompting from us, any really teaching that

276
00:14:23,750 --> 00:14:29,875
behavior, that tells you how effective it is and how well it works. And in fact, many successful

277
00:14:29,935 --> 00:14:35,260
creators have used lucky rituals. For example, Mary Shelley had a boa constrictor around her

278
00:14:35,300 --> 00:14:40,384
neck while she wrote, and she would interpret how the boa constrictor was acting and moving

279
00:14:41,525 --> 00:14:43,406
to determine whether she was done writing for the day.

280
00:14:44,409 --> 00:14:46,230
Charles Dickens actually had a compass with him

281
00:14:46,250 --> 00:14:47,311
that he carried all the time.

282
00:14:47,752 --> 00:14:51,274
And he always slept with him and facing north.

283
00:14:52,155 --> 00:14:55,657
So there's tremendous use of superstition as a tool,

284
00:14:56,218 --> 00:14:57,078
as a mental tool.

285
00:14:57,639 --> 00:14:59,100
And we want to use it to leverage

286
00:14:59,540 --> 00:15:01,982
those internal mechanisms to build self-confidence

287
00:15:02,102 --> 00:15:03,142
and self-esteem.

288
00:15:06,065 --> 00:15:09,387
And then finally, creative therapy actually works too.

289
00:15:10,620 --> 00:15:13,301
Creative exercises have been shown to reduce pain, anxiety,

290
00:15:13,381 --> 00:15:16,443
and depression and stress while increasing self-esteem

291
00:15:17,183 --> 00:15:18,624
and improving the quality of life.

292
00:15:19,704 --> 00:15:22,686
Creativity itself has that effect.

293
00:15:22,726 --> 00:15:25,187
It doesn't matter how good you are at it

294
00:15:25,367 --> 00:15:27,788
or what you produce at the end of it.

295
00:15:28,328 --> 00:15:31,030
It's the act of creativity that has the therapeutic effects.

296
00:15:31,757 --> 00:15:35,219
And so I say all of these things knowing that inherently,

297
00:15:35,780 --> 00:15:38,902
most people in game development are skeptics of science

298
00:15:38,962 --> 00:15:40,163
when it comes to things like this.

299
00:15:40,803 --> 00:15:43,265
We're absolutely believers in science and everything else,

300
00:15:43,905 --> 00:15:46,086
but we tend to dismiss things like superstition

301
00:15:46,266 --> 00:15:48,448
and visualization and even ritual itself

302
00:15:49,248 --> 00:15:51,690
because it's sometimes easier to dismiss those

303
00:15:52,270 --> 00:15:53,331
than to see them as tools.

304
00:15:54,212 --> 00:15:56,833
And so I understand that sense.

305
00:15:56,893 --> 00:15:57,974
I understand that sentiment.

306
00:15:58,740 --> 00:16:01,482
but somehow ritual and visualization and superstition

307
00:16:01,502 --> 00:16:05,223
and creativity and game dev just don't belong

308
00:16:05,243 --> 00:16:08,125
in the same process together.

309
00:16:08,585 --> 00:16:09,465
But I can tell you they do.

310
00:16:09,485 --> 00:16:10,946
And I can tell you that game development

311
00:16:11,446 --> 00:16:14,248
is the answer for burnout in game development.

312
00:16:14,808 --> 00:16:16,329
And that's not just because it's the hair

313
00:16:16,349 --> 00:16:17,249
of the dog that bit you.

314
00:16:17,869 --> 00:16:22,471
So here's some reasons that you can use a solo game project

315
00:16:23,092 --> 00:16:24,132
to battle your burnout.

316
00:16:25,386 --> 00:16:28,548
First is that one thing that causes a lot of workplace stress

317
00:16:28,588 --> 00:16:31,429
and game development is that you are constantly in,

318
00:16:32,430 --> 00:16:35,291
for most people, under deadline, under stress,

319
00:16:35,851 --> 00:16:36,872
trying to get things done,

320
00:16:37,432 --> 00:16:39,173
trying to make sure those things coordinate

321
00:16:39,193 --> 00:16:40,634
with what the rest of the team is doing.

322
00:16:41,134 --> 00:16:44,116
And you have somebody who's telling you what to create.

323
00:16:45,316 --> 00:16:46,697
And that's true for almost everybody.

324
00:16:47,197 --> 00:16:49,018
Even if you're an executive at a game company,

325
00:16:49,158 --> 00:16:50,119
I can say from experience,

326
00:16:50,619 --> 00:16:52,480
I still had a boss who was telling me what to do.

327
00:16:53,138 --> 00:16:56,460
So in my side projects though, no one could tell me what to do.

328
00:16:57,181 --> 00:17:02,385
And that was when I especially was under stress during a project at any given time.

329
00:17:03,085 --> 00:17:07,168
Or if I felt like I didn't agree with the decisions that were being made,

330
00:17:07,449 --> 00:17:11,171
it was tremendously helpful for me to come home and work on something where no one could tell me

331
00:17:11,211 --> 00:17:16,795
what to do. It also means you can focus on variety, make something new and exciting,

332
00:17:17,136 --> 00:17:19,017
learn new skills, do things you haven't done before.

333
00:17:21,272 --> 00:17:23,292
it gives you tremendous freedom to express yourself.

334
00:17:24,113 --> 00:17:27,314
Most of us don't get to actually express everything

335
00:17:27,394 --> 00:17:29,535
in who we are as a part of the games that we're making,

336
00:17:30,155 --> 00:17:31,896
usually because we're making those in collaboration

337
00:17:31,916 --> 00:17:32,556
with other people.

338
00:17:34,096 --> 00:17:37,118
But it also lets you express yourself in other ways.

339
00:17:37,178 --> 00:17:39,799
It doesn't mean every game you make has to be a message

340
00:17:39,839 --> 00:17:40,939
game with a capital M.

341
00:17:41,836 --> 00:17:47,079
It can let you express yourself in terms of making that game you voice that sounded fun,

342
00:17:47,199 --> 00:17:51,741
but maybe three other people besides you would want to play. That's expressing yourself too.

343
00:17:52,902 --> 00:17:57,384
But the bottom line and the thing that I found ultimately most helpful about having a game dev

344
00:17:57,424 --> 00:18:02,046
side project is I can make whatever the hell I want and nobody could tell me any differently.

345
00:18:02,787 --> 00:18:08,090
And that freedom of just being my own boss really made a difference to me.

346
00:18:09,177 --> 00:18:14,682
So here's how all of these puzzle pieces fit together into the side project ritual.

347
00:18:15,823 --> 00:18:18,825
It is eight steps and we're going to start with step one which is the opening.

348
00:18:23,489 --> 00:18:27,573
So the opening of any ritual has a purpose. Every step has a purpose,

349
00:18:27,593 --> 00:18:32,758
but the opening is particularly important. It triggers our superstitions.

350
00:18:33,558 --> 00:18:35,860
And it tells your brain that you're switching modes,

351
00:18:35,920 --> 00:18:37,461
that this thing that's about to come up,

352
00:18:37,661 --> 00:18:40,283
you understand what it is, and you know what you're

353
00:18:40,303 --> 00:18:43,365
going to be doing, and that it's important.

354
00:18:44,206 --> 00:18:47,228
So before you start envisioning wind chimes and whale song,

355
00:18:48,449 --> 00:18:49,790
it's about what's important to you.

356
00:18:50,211 --> 00:18:53,873
So you want to collect inspirational items, images,

357
00:18:53,934 --> 00:18:56,215
music, practices, because again, you're

358
00:18:56,255 --> 00:18:57,456
triggering your brain that you're

359
00:18:57,476 --> 00:18:58,517
getting ready to do the work.

360
00:19:00,038 --> 00:19:01,800
You definitely want to give some thought to superstition.

361
00:19:02,440 --> 00:19:04,882
And look, if you don't have things that you will consider lucky now,

362
00:19:05,603 --> 00:19:09,546
start to try to build those superstitions. Think about, you know, if I have

363
00:19:11,127 --> 00:19:15,670
green tea while I'm working, it's going to help me work faster or it's

364
00:19:15,690 --> 00:19:18,412
going to help me work better. Try to build those links for yourself.

365
00:19:19,813 --> 00:19:23,055
And again, so you don't think it has to be a whale song.

366
00:19:23,535 --> 00:19:24,916
Let's look at an example.

367
00:19:24,936 --> 00:19:29,159
Dad! Dad!

368
00:19:32,734 --> 00:19:33,314
It's important!

369
00:19:33,514 --> 00:19:35,035
Then wait, count to twenty.

370
00:19:35,296 --> 00:19:36,256
No, Dad! Do you listen?

371
00:19:36,296 --> 00:19:36,777
Junior!

372
00:19:37,737 --> 00:19:39,378
One, two, three, four...

373
00:19:39,859 --> 00:19:40,259
In Greek.

374
00:19:40,359 --> 00:19:41,140
Ena...

375
00:19:41,360 --> 00:19:41,980
...dio...

376
00:19:42,841 --> 00:19:43,261
...dia.

377
00:19:43,661 --> 00:19:44,922
Tessera...

378
00:19:44,962 --> 00:19:45,202
...dente...

379
00:20:04,457 --> 00:20:05,238
So did you catch it?

