00:23:55,665 --> 00:23:57,787
it should be and will be as unique as you are.

448
00:23:59,728 --> 00:24:00,429
So step two.

449
00:24:01,253 --> 00:24:03,695
and the side ritual is the sacred space and time.

450
00:24:04,255 --> 00:24:05,895
Now, when I say sacred, I don't mean religious.

451
00:24:06,816 --> 00:24:10,217
I mean, for example, sacrosanct or regarded with great respect

452
00:24:10,337 --> 00:24:10,918
and reverence.

453
00:24:11,538 --> 00:24:14,319
So when you set up your space, you

454
00:24:14,339 --> 00:24:16,140
want to have a dedicated space.

455
00:24:16,260 --> 00:24:18,101
You're in the same spot every day if you can be.

456
00:24:18,121 --> 00:24:20,002
And it can be really small.

457
00:24:20,042 --> 00:24:21,162
It can be the corner of a kitchen.

458
00:24:22,102 --> 00:24:24,924
You just want to have room to display some objects that

459
00:24:24,944 --> 00:24:25,944
are inspirational to you.

460
00:24:25,964 --> 00:24:28,725
And they don't have to be, again, religious or mystical.

461
00:24:29,226 --> 00:24:30,046
They can be whatever.

462
00:24:31,102 --> 00:24:31,883
It has meaning to you.

463
00:24:33,525 --> 00:24:34,866
You do need to be left alone, though.

464
00:24:35,707 --> 00:24:37,268
So noise-canceling headphones can

465
00:24:37,308 --> 00:24:38,589
help when you're in a shared space,

466
00:24:38,669 --> 00:24:41,932
but also just letting the people that you share your home with

467
00:24:42,653 --> 00:24:48,238
know that when at a certain time of day or night,

468
00:24:49,199 --> 00:24:51,981
you need to be left alone for a certain period of time,

469
00:24:52,001 --> 00:24:54,604
like an hour or two hours, because that's

470
00:24:54,644 --> 00:24:55,365
your focus time.

471
00:24:56,884 --> 00:24:59,346
You also want to gather your tools together into this space.

472
00:24:59,907 --> 00:25:01,588
Most people, of course, think of hardware and software

473
00:25:01,608 --> 00:25:02,869
because we're talking about game development,

474
00:25:03,450 --> 00:25:05,732
but it can also be things like timers.

475
00:25:05,892 --> 00:25:09,695
If you are a big fan of things like the Pomodoro technique,

476
00:25:10,196 --> 00:25:13,679
it can be timers to plan different work sessions.

477
00:25:14,459 --> 00:25:15,901
It can include music themed

478
00:25:15,981 --> 00:25:17,342
for whatever it is that you're working on,

479
00:25:17,862 --> 00:25:20,164
but it can also include things like scent or light.

480
00:25:20,264 --> 00:25:20,885
So it could be,

481
00:25:22,742 --> 00:25:27,747
a candle that smells like evergreens if you're working on something that takes place in a forest,

482
00:25:27,767 --> 00:25:33,453
or light that imitates sunlight to help you feel better during that time, or dim lighting that

483
00:25:33,493 --> 00:25:37,637
makes you feel like it's an escape from the rest of your day, whatever works for you.

484
00:25:40,020 --> 00:25:43,663
And the time is sacred too, so you want to decide how much time you're going to spend

485
00:25:43,743 --> 00:25:45,385
and then you're going to commit to that time.

486
00:25:46,376 --> 00:25:48,237
Committing means you're going to block out distractions.

487
00:25:48,277 --> 00:25:52,238
You're not going to spend that time surfing the web, answering emails.

488
00:25:52,258 --> 00:25:54,519
You're not going to do things that are unrelated to what you're working on.

489
00:25:55,799 --> 00:25:58,360
You're also going to persist even when it's frustrating.

490
00:25:59,240 --> 00:26:00,281
What I mean by that is,

491
00:26:00,401 --> 00:26:02,542
you're going to use that time for something creative,

492
00:26:02,702 --> 00:26:04,802
even if it means switching tasks.

493
00:26:04,942 --> 00:26:07,683
If you are working on your game and you're working on code,

494
00:26:07,743 --> 00:26:10,044
and you feel completely stuck and you just can't do it today,

495
00:26:10,885 --> 00:26:13,625
switch to drawing, switch to making music,

496
00:26:13,665 --> 00:26:14,806
switch to working on audio.

497
00:26:15,757 --> 00:26:19,139
It can even be not related to the project if you have to, like adult coloring books,

498
00:26:19,199 --> 00:26:22,922
things like that. Just do something creative for that space of time.

499
00:26:25,304 --> 00:26:29,707
And always remind yourself that this is your time. It's not an obligation. It's a gift that

500
00:26:29,727 --> 00:26:34,671
you're making to yourself. And over time, as you do the ritual more and more, you'll start

501
00:26:34,691 --> 00:26:39,074
to look forward to it and actually really jealously guard your ritual time.

502
00:26:41,718 --> 00:26:43,739
So step three is mindfulness.

503
00:26:43,799 --> 00:26:47,000
Now, everybody thinks of meditation first when you mention mindfulness.

504
00:26:47,040 --> 00:26:49,562
And yes, meditation is good.

505
00:26:49,582 --> 00:26:51,823
A couple of different things that you can try,

506
00:26:51,843 --> 00:26:54,004
because we're only going to meditate for two to three minutes.

507
00:26:54,104 --> 00:26:55,104
It's a very short session.

508
00:26:55,685 --> 00:26:59,767
You can do three minutes of breathing where you spend those three minutes

509
00:26:59,827 --> 00:27:03,468
being aware of each breath you take.

510
00:27:03,508 --> 00:27:07,310
You try to breathe in a certain rhythm and you try to be aware

511
00:27:07,430 --> 00:27:10,212
of how the breath feels going in and out of your body.

512
00:27:12,688 --> 00:27:14,489
There's something else called visualize the river.

513
00:27:14,529 --> 00:27:18,352
And this is what I used when I was trying

514
00:27:18,432 --> 00:27:21,474
to cope with cancer diagnosis.

515
00:27:22,815 --> 00:27:25,497
So I would envision myself laying on my back,

516
00:27:25,817 --> 00:27:26,858
floating in a river.

517
00:27:28,239 --> 00:27:30,820
And for about 30 seconds, I'll just float in the river

518
00:27:30,920 --> 00:27:33,002
and really even play sound effects

519
00:27:33,062 --> 00:27:35,163
and really immerse myself in that sense

520
00:27:35,223 --> 00:27:36,004
of floating in the river.

521
00:27:36,943 --> 00:27:39,864
And then whatever it is that is distracting me or bothering me,

522
00:27:40,364 --> 00:27:44,025
I'll picture myself actually bundling it up in my head,

523
00:27:44,045 --> 00:27:46,105
like reaching into my head and taking it out.

524
00:27:47,185 --> 00:27:49,126
And I feel it in my hand for a second.

525
00:27:49,806 --> 00:27:51,506
And then I set it in the river beside me.

526
00:27:51,746 --> 00:27:53,946
And now I watch it float along with me.

527
00:27:54,827 --> 00:27:56,187
And after about a minute of that,

528
00:27:57,167 --> 00:27:58,487
I make the decision to let it go.

529
00:27:59,547 --> 00:28:01,088
It's going to be floating in the river with me.

530
00:28:01,188 --> 00:28:03,048
When the time comes, it will still be there.

531
00:28:03,068 --> 00:28:05,808
I just don't need to carry it along with me right now.

532
00:28:07,814 --> 00:28:11,876
You can also repeat a mantra and it doesn't have to be OM or anything like official.

533
00:28:12,456 --> 00:28:17,699
It can be things like I'm here, I'm present or my favorite mantra from a guided meditation that

534
00:28:17,739 --> 00:28:25,382
I used to love. In this moment, everything is okay. But mindfulness doesn't have to be meditation.

535
00:28:25,422 --> 00:28:31,885
There are other ways that you can be mindful. So attentive listening is one way and that is

536
00:28:32,125 --> 00:28:37,087
finding a sound that you find interesting or intriguing.

537
00:28:37,632 --> 00:28:44,515
like a sound of a forest and spending three minutes actually paying attention to it,

538
00:28:45,236 --> 00:28:49,958
really listening to it, trying to pick apart all of the different sounds in it and how often do

539
00:28:49,998 --> 00:28:57,681
you hear them and what do you think they mean. Then there is the raisin exercise which is as

540
00:28:57,761 --> 00:29:03,544
fun as it sounds. You take a small piece of food and you act like you're from another planet and

541
00:29:03,564 --> 00:29:04,544
you've never seen it before.

542
00:29:05,277 --> 00:29:11,681
and you spend the three minutes just looking at it and marveling at it and feeling the texture of it

543
00:29:11,942 --> 00:29:18,226
and smelling it and tasting a little bit of it. Really paying attention to that thing as if you've

544
00:29:18,266 --> 00:29:19,047
never seen it before.

545
00:29:20,852 --> 00:29:21,993
And then mindful seeing.

546
00:29:22,033 --> 00:29:24,214
So mindful seeing is similar to attentive listening.

547
00:29:24,575 --> 00:29:25,635
It's just visual instead.

548
00:29:26,156 --> 00:29:28,117
So you take, you know, you can look out your own window

549
00:29:28,697 --> 00:29:31,619
or for example, on Netflix, there are videos of,

550
00:29:31,679 --> 00:29:33,901
for example, a train going through Sweden for an hour.

551
00:29:34,401 --> 00:29:35,682
So you can take those videos

552
00:29:36,062 --> 00:29:39,324
and just spend three minutes watching it carefully

553
00:29:39,344 --> 00:29:42,146
and just being very mindful about everything

554
00:29:42,166 --> 00:29:44,287
that you're seeing happening, every dust moat,

555
00:29:44,787 --> 00:29:47,429
the wind moving leaves of grass, right?

556
00:29:47,769 --> 00:29:50,211
Very specifically looking at that carefully.

557
00:29:51,562 --> 00:29:54,803
And there are also sound effects and other gadgets

558
00:29:55,343 --> 00:29:58,564
that you can use to help you focus during these sessions,

559
00:29:59,264 --> 00:30:01,145
like singing bowls.

560
00:30:07,547 --> 00:30:08,047
Bonsai.

561
00:30:08,888 --> 00:30:11,409
Taking three to four to five minutes

562
00:30:12,189 --> 00:30:16,310
and trimming and really lovingly caring for a bonsai tree

563
00:30:16,390 --> 00:30:18,331
is one of the most meditative things that you can do.

564
00:30:20,789 --> 00:30:23,091
There are various applications that can help you.

565
00:30:24,572 --> 00:30:25,953
It's Buddhify over there on the left.

566
00:30:26,453 --> 00:30:28,114
Buddhify is super great with short session,

567
00:30:29,035 --> 00:30:31,977
especially for short session meditations that

568
00:30:31,997 --> 00:30:33,157
happen while you're doing something else,

569
00:30:33,858 --> 00:30:35,699
like walking to work or taking a break at work

570
00:30:35,959 --> 00:30:37,881
or about to go to sleep.

571
00:30:38,801 --> 00:30:41,423
I use Headspace myself and very much like it,

572
00:30:41,463 --> 00:30:43,244
but I've also heard really good things about Calm.

573
00:30:44,825 --> 00:30:46,827
And there are actually gadgets that

574
00:30:46,867 --> 00:30:49,669
help with meditation, specifically with coherence,

575
00:30:49,789 --> 00:30:50,229
most of them.

576
00:30:51,423 --> 00:30:54,524
I haven't used the Muse, but I've used the technology in Unite,

577
00:30:54,644 --> 00:30:56,605
which that company used to be called Wild Divine.

578
00:30:56,625 --> 00:30:59,066
I've also used HeartMath,

579
00:30:59,086 --> 00:31:00,046
that's what I have right now.

580
00:31:01,126 --> 00:31:07,529
Coherence is when your breathing and heart rate are in coherence, they're aligned.

581
00:31:08,429 --> 00:31:11,730
In that state, that's the state that naturally occurs with meditation.

582
00:31:12,651 --> 00:31:15,312
In that state, you have enhanced.

583
00:31:16,466 --> 00:31:18,907
senses and enhanced sense of well-being as well.

584
00:31:19,647 --> 00:31:21,747
What the gadgets can do is they can help you

585
00:31:21,848 --> 00:31:24,568
understand the feeling of when you're in that state.

586
00:31:25,429 --> 00:31:27,789
You can achieve that state without the gadgets as well.

587
00:31:30,930 --> 00:31:32,531
Then after the mindfulness, you're going to spend

588
00:31:32,571 --> 00:31:34,211
a few minutes on your focused goals.

589
00:31:36,492 --> 00:31:37,792
You're going to review the work you did in

590
00:31:37,812 --> 00:31:39,433
the last session for about five minutes

591
00:31:39,913 --> 00:31:41,393
and make note of any revisions you have,

592
00:31:41,413 --> 00:31:42,553
but that's getting your head back in

593
00:31:42,573 --> 00:31:44,554
the space of what you were working on.

594
00:31:45,186 --> 00:31:49,709
And taking dedicated time to do that means you're not spending your actual work time,

595
00:31:50,989 --> 00:31:54,151
getting a little bit of the ways down the road and then saying, wait, what was I doing again?

596
00:31:54,771 --> 00:31:57,433
So you're going to take the time to review and get that all in your head first.

597
00:31:58,814 --> 00:32:02,335
And then you're going to look at the focus goals that you had at the end of your last session.

598
00:32:02,416 --> 00:32:06,017
So since those are created at the end of the last session, I'm going to talk about those a little

599
00:32:06,037 --> 00:32:13,121
bit later. And then it's time to do the work. And I use the phrase do the work intentionally.

600
00:32:13,712 --> 00:32:16,654
because that's the phrase that Stephen Pressfield uses in The War of Art.

601
00:32:17,475 --> 00:32:26,841
He also talks about something called resistance. Resistance is the invisible force that stops you

602
00:32:26,941 --> 00:32:31,904
from doing your work. And I think we've all experienced it in one form or another.

603
00:32:31,924 --> 00:32:34,386
And he always says it's the if

604
00:32:35,235 --> 00:32:38,699
It's the thing that stops you from actually working out because working out is good for you.

605
00:32:39,079 --> 00:32:42,943
It's the thing that stops you from eating the healthy stuff instead of the unhealthy stuff

606
00:32:42,983 --> 00:32:49,529
because the healthy stuff is good for you. So he says there's a secret that real writers know

607
00:32:49,689 --> 00:32:53,993
that wannabe writers don't and the secret is this. It's not the writing part that's hard.

608
00:32:54,594 --> 00:32:58,898
What's hard is sitting down to write. What keeps us from sitting down is resistance.

609
00:33:00,795 --> 00:33:06,476
And he goes on to say, most of us have two lives, the life we live and the unlived life within us.

610
00:33:07,216 --> 00:33:08,897
Between the two stands resistance.

611
00:33:09,817 --> 00:33:14,138
Resistance cannot be seen, touched, heard or smelled, but it can be felt.

612
00:33:14,938 --> 00:33:19,879
We all experience it as an energy field radiating from a work in potential.

613
00:33:20,640 --> 00:33:21,860
It's a repelling force.

614
00:33:22,220 --> 00:33:22,900
It's negative.

615
00:33:23,600 --> 00:33:28,462
Its aim is to shove us away, distract us, to prevent us from doing our work.

616
00:33:29,448 --> 00:33:38,191
And I say all of that because you need to focus on doing the work and you need to end resistance and understand when it's happening.

617
00:33:39,291 --> 00:33:41,152
So of course first you'll need to choose a project.

618
00:33:42,112 --> 00:33:46,353
Whatever you choose, it doesn't have to be your final answer. It just needs to be something that you plan to ship.

619
00:33:46,973 --> 00:33:48,894
It can be really small, but you need to plan to ship it.

620
00:33:49,941 --> 00:33:54,603
The act of knowing you're going to complete something changes the tone of your work.

621
00:33:54,643 --> 00:33:59,004
And I think that's an important part of this process is belief that you're going to ship it

622
00:33:59,024 --> 00:34:04,386
when you're done. Then, of course, you need to choose your weapon as well, which is, you know,

623
00:34:04,426 --> 00:34:08,207
kind of for game development, hand in hand with the project that you want to undertake.

624
00:34:09,167 --> 00:34:13,469
So it can be physical games. If you want to get away from working in the digital, which you do

625
00:34:13,489 --> 00:34:13,789
all day.

626
00:34:14,883 --> 00:34:16,744
There's some great narrative game tools out there.

627
00:34:17,164 --> 00:34:19,365
This is actually a screenshot from my narrative game,

628
00:34:20,025 --> 00:34:22,606
which I'm building in ChoiceScript for choice of games.

629
00:34:23,646 --> 00:34:25,307
But there are things like Twine and Inform

630
00:34:25,327 --> 00:34:26,027
that are great too.

631
00:34:28,308 --> 00:34:29,488
There's some really simple game tools

632
00:34:29,508 --> 00:34:31,208
that focus just on the act of creation

633
00:34:31,288 --> 00:34:32,329
and not on the tool itself.

634
00:34:32,829 --> 00:34:34,950
Things like Game Maker, RPG Maker, and Pico 8.

635
00:34:36,777 --> 00:34:39,438
And of course, Unity and Unreal are always available.

636
00:34:40,018 --> 00:34:41,559
So a little bit of a practical note,

637
00:34:41,779 --> 00:34:43,079
a lot of people in game development

638
00:34:43,119 --> 00:34:47,001
work under IP agreements and or restrictions

639
00:34:47,081 --> 00:34:49,502
from mood lighting or commercial side projects.

640
00:34:50,302 --> 00:34:53,243
Those suck and are often, and I'm not saying,

641
00:34:53,344 --> 00:34:54,384
this is not legal advice,

642
00:34:54,824 --> 00:34:56,925
but they're often unenforceable anyway.

643
00:34:57,545 --> 00:34:58,866
But even if they're unenforceable,

644
00:34:59,106 --> 00:35:01,827
it's got a chilling effect because no one wants to

645
00:35:02,703 --> 00:35:07,087
be the person that sounds like you're distracted from your main game that you're working on for

646
00:35:07,127 --> 00:35:11,871
work by this side game. I know personally I was never distracted by my side project,

647
00:35:12,411 --> 00:35:18,476
but it still I felt odd even bringing it up when I had permission when I had to get permission for

648
00:35:18,496 --> 00:35:23,520
a side project. So if you're in that situation and I'm not saying to be a secret squirrel

649
00:35:24,261 --> 00:35:28,024
and work on it secretly, it's a terrible idea. What I am saying is you can do things like game mods.

650
00:35:29,136 --> 00:35:33,440
Game mods are things that avoid the IP issues

651
00:35:33,520 --> 00:35:34,921
because they're always owned by the company

652
00:35:34,961 --> 00:35:36,021
that released the original game.

653
00:35:36,682 --> 00:35:38,603
So things like Skyrim or Fallout, for example,

654
00:35:38,643 --> 00:35:40,685
have creator kits and so do other games.

655
00:35:41,846 --> 00:35:43,187
You can participate in game jams

656
00:35:43,587 --> 00:35:44,648
that starts with your spark,

657
00:35:45,249 --> 00:35:48,011
and then you can finish that small project

658
00:35:48,051 --> 00:35:49,872
and release it for free as a part of the game jam.

659
00:35:51,933 --> 00:35:55,374
Or if you feel completely blocked by your IP agreements,

660
00:35:55,934 --> 00:35:58,255
there are always things like woodworking and papercraft

661
00:35:58,335 --> 00:35:58,855
and knitting.

662
00:35:58,915 --> 00:36:00,615
And often some of those can become games,

663
00:36:01,295 --> 00:36:02,576
can become releasable games.

664
00:36:02,636 --> 00:36:04,696
It's interesting to think about physical games

665
00:36:04,736 --> 00:36:06,096
from glassmaking, for example.

666
00:36:06,616 --> 00:36:09,017
But it's just another way to express yourself.

667
00:36:10,897 --> 00:36:12,798
You want to think about your key skills

668
00:36:12,858 --> 00:36:14,278
and make sure whatever you're working on,

669
00:36:14,778 --> 00:36:16,538
you have at least one key skill that's

670
00:36:16,558 --> 00:36:17,418
going to contribute to it.

671
00:36:18,067 --> 00:36:20,048
You don't want to try something that's all new for you

672
00:36:20,108 --> 00:36:22,150
because you'll feel like you're constantly failing.

673
00:36:22,730 --> 00:36:24,151
But you do want a little bit of new,

674
00:36:24,211 --> 00:36:25,792
a little bit of something you don't do in

675
00:36:25,812 --> 00:36:27,434
your day job because you want this to feel like

676
00:36:27,454 --> 00:36:29,835
an opportunity to do something different.

677
00:36:31,517 --> 00:36:32,738
Ultimately, of course, you'll find

678
00:36:32,778 --> 00:36:34,539
yourself staring at this blank page.

679
00:36:34,659 --> 00:36:36,040
Blank page is my nemesis.

680
00:36:36,841 --> 00:36:38,722
I'm actually terrible at dealing with the blank page.

681
00:36:39,437 --> 00:36:44,319
So one of the things that I've learned to do is in whatever form I'm documenting or writing down

682
00:36:44,359 --> 00:36:50,241
ideas for this game, whether it's a physical notebook or Google Docs or whatever, I make a

683
00:36:50,261 --> 00:36:56,184
page called Scratch. And on the Scratch page, I can type in any idea I have, any thought I have,

684
00:36:56,224 --> 00:37:00,325
any link I have, anything that I think is useful. And the fact that it's not

685
00:37:01,394 --> 00:37:06,376
intended to be final, it's just intended to be a space to collect things, means I feel safe

686
00:37:06,456 --> 00:37:10,618
typing in there. And a lot of times when I'm stuck on the blank page, I'll go to my scratch page and

687
00:37:10,638 --> 00:37:15,841
just start typing stream of consciousness. And over time, I'll end up in a place where I feel

688
00:37:15,861 --> 00:37:21,203
like, okay, I can work now. And also a lot of good ideas will come from it. You also need to

689
00:37:21,243 --> 00:37:27,786
teach yourself to let go. We work in an industry where it's important that all of us know what

690
00:37:27,806 --> 00:37:30,427
we're building and what to do now and how it all.

691
00:37:31,125 --> 00:37:36,490
ladders up to the same goal and how it all works together. And that can feel really inhibiting

692
00:37:36,730 --> 00:37:40,134
when you're working on a solo project. I know personally, it was one of the hardest things that

693
00:37:40,154 --> 00:37:47,220
I had to get over was feeling like I can't work because I don't know everything that I need to

694
00:37:47,260 --> 00:37:51,425
build. But in this, you don't have to plan for everything. That's a part of the joy with a side

695
00:37:51,465 --> 00:37:56,509
project is that you actually can let go. But you absolutely do need to commit.

696
00:37:57,456 --> 00:38:00,978
even if that means you're going to whittle until you uncover the shape of your game.

697
00:38:01,338 --> 00:38:06,141
You're going to commit to spending that time. Something else that you should do as a part of

698
00:38:06,181 --> 00:38:10,684
doing the work is to find a way to talk about it. You want a direct connection between people

699
00:38:11,565 --> 00:38:16,167
and your personal work. And the reason that you want that is because it's going to keep

700
00:38:16,187 --> 00:38:22,091
you accountable and engaged and purposeful. Being under contract for my side project right now

701
00:38:22,391 --> 00:38:25,253
means I'm going to finish it because people are expecting it.

702
00:38:26,044 --> 00:38:30,386
So you can stream your development on Twitch or Facebook, for example, but find a way to

703
00:38:30,987 --> 00:38:35,090
build some anticipation, even if it's just with friends, because that will keep you accountable.

704
00:38:38,652 --> 00:38:42,455
So then we're going to have a moment of purposeful goals.

705
00:38:43,895 --> 00:38:46,978
You're going to save your work. Super important, obviously.

706
00:38:46,998 --> 00:38:50,360
Didn't want to not mention that and have that not be a part of the process.

707
00:38:50,780 --> 00:38:53,722
We all do it routinely, but certainly do it at the end of your session.

708
00:38:54,779 --> 00:38:56,320
you're going to make your to-dos.

709
00:38:57,080 --> 00:38:59,402
And what you're going to do in the process of making

710
00:38:59,422 --> 00:39:01,844
those to-dos is you're going to add a context.

711
00:39:02,345 --> 00:39:03,506
So this is something that I learned

712
00:39:03,546 --> 00:39:07,089
as a part of the getting things done approach to productivity.

713
00:39:07,890 --> 00:39:11,332
A context means the place where you can actually

714
00:39:11,473 --> 00:39:13,354
do the thing in question.

715
00:39:13,995 --> 00:39:15,756
And the reason I set different contexts

716
00:39:15,876 --> 00:39:20,580
is because I learned that there are different mental spaces

717
00:39:20,640 --> 00:39:22,041
where I can do different things.

718
00:39:22,750 --> 00:39:26,691
Like, if it's complex code that I need to write, I need to be at my desk 100%.

719
00:39:26,811 --> 00:39:30,232
Can't do it anywhere else. If it's something I need to think through,

720
00:39:30,292 --> 00:39:33,792
a problem I need to solve, like, how can you find out about this thing before this other

721
00:39:33,832 --> 00:39:37,493
thing has happened in this story? A lot of times I can do that while I'm walking,

722
00:39:37,553 --> 00:39:43,135
while I'm using an exercise bike. I will find a time that is sort of action-oriented

723
00:39:45,135 --> 00:39:47,916
where I'm not trying to write or do anything else at the same time.

724
00:39:48,376 --> 00:39:51,377
So I'll make it to do walking task for that.

725
00:39:52,125 --> 00:39:56,088
On my phone, there are certain things I can do from a narrative perspective. There's certain

726
00:39:56,128 --> 00:40:00,612
writing things I can do on my phone. Lots of things I can't, but some I can. So the ones

727
00:40:00,652 --> 00:40:04,435
that can't be done on my phone, I will make a note of that. So when I'm waiting at the doctor's

728
00:40:04,515 --> 00:40:10,219
office or killing 15 minutes in bed before I try to fall asleep, I will actually pull up my phone

729
00:40:10,239 --> 00:40:11,120
and start working on those.

730
00:40:15,765 --> 00:40:18,045
And then we're going to have a moment of gratitude.

